Description: This project focused on the removal of twelve remaining check dams from within Fife Creek in Armstrong Redwoods State Reserve. Removal of the check dams is a component of a comprehensive program geared toward the restoration of predevelopment processes and biota to the Fife Creek watershed.

The County of Ventura Parks Department removed the Ojai Valley Trail dry weather crossing at the San Antonio Creek and replaced it with a single span bridge in an effort to provide an additional 15 miles of habitat for migrating steelhead trout. The addition of a bridge designed to pass a 100-year flood event is also expected to improve public safety at the site, which often becomes impassable during storms.

This project will remove barriers to fish passage in Maria Ygnacio Creek. The project will implement engineered designs that call for several improvements to the creek: removal of a low flow crossing, regrading of the stream channel, installation of engineered stream bed material, installation of a new clear span bridge, and restoration with native riparian vegetation at the site.

The Rodeo Grounds Berm was 1000ft long by 40-100ft wide and was placed directly in the channel of Topanga Creek. This project removed the berm and restored riparian habitat in Topanga Creek. Berm removal resulted in 3000 linear feet of connectivity critical for migrating steelhead trout, as well as invasive species removal and establishment of native wetland and riparian communities on over 12 acres of floodplain. Snorkel surveys after restoration revealed trout ranging from five to eight inches using newly formed pools in the restored channel.
This structure was just downstream of the San Clemente dam. It impedes Steelhead Passage, and it will contribute to the 25 miles of spawining and rearing habitat of these fish.

Second largest dam removal in California. The dam is also causing safety issues. The banks of the lake have eroded due to the unnatural wave action caused by the lake and sediment accumulation upstream of the dam. The lake is surrounded by redwood trees, but erosion is causing the banks to be unstable, and they are toppling over. The dam itself is in poor repair and could become a liability.

Removal of four water diversion dams and 12 unscreened water diversions are resulting in dramatic improvements to 25 miles of chinook salmon habitat in the Sacramento Valley’s Butte Creek.  The collaborative effort includes one of northern California’s largest irrigation districts, rice growers and other agricultural interests, government resource agencies, and other stakeholders.  The group worked together to solve individual and mutual problems, with a primary goal of restoring the fisheries.  The project is making important progress toward protecting chinook salmon, which are listed as threatened under California’s Endangered Species Act.  In 1987, only 14 spring-run chinook salmon were found spawning in Butte Creek.  The removal of four small dams and other river restoration efforts contributed to a record spring 1998 run of more than 20,000 adult chinooks.

Description: This project involved the removal of Dennett Dam, an abandoned low-head dam located on the lower Tuolumne River in Modesto, California. The dam has been an instream barrier to anadromous fish passage, controlling local hydraulic and sediment transport conditions, for over 60 years, while also impeding water flow in the river. It is also a significant safety hazard adjacent to a major park, and has been the location of three drowning deaths in the last five years, including two children.
Owner: Present Owner Unknown (or they don't want to be known). Built by the City of Modesto and condemned by the State of California in the 1940's or 1950's. Riverbed in CA is owned by the State.

Description: This dam was located in the high alpine wilderness of Northern Colorado, in Rocky Mountain National Park. With establishment of the park in 1915, the dam became a safety liability as well as an eyesore in an otherwise pristine wilderness area. In 1982, following the failure of Lawn Lake Dam (also located in the park), the City of Longmont was ordered to repair or breach Bluebird Dam. In 1987, the National Park Service purchased from the city the water rights and easements associated with Bluebird Dam.
This structure was removed after being severely damaged during the September 2013 flooding, which affected much of Colorado. Earth material contained behind the dam was used to rebuild US Highway 34.
As part of the Sterling Natural Area Restoration project by the City of Fort Collins in partnership with the Colorado Water Trust, the Josh Ames Diversion Dam was removed in November 2013.

The Hotchkiss Diversion Structure, or Chipeta Dam, was once used to divert water to the Hotchkiss Fish Hatchery. The obsolete structure reached more than 150 feet across the North Fork, trapped boaters, prevented fish migration and created isolated populations of fish. In 2006 NFRIA removed most of the concrete structure, though some pieces were buried deep in the channel as an easy means of bank stabilization. A newly graded bank and river stretch with a riffle-pool-run sequence allows for native and sport fish to thrive in a stretch that was previously occupied by large, non-native carp. Four new rock structures protect banks from erosion, provide habitat for aquatic life, and create fun hydraulics for boaters. The re-graded, re-vegetated floodplain will also allow flood energy to dissipate safely during high water over smooth banks. Seven new willow “silt fences” were planted on either side of the river. These fences stabilize banks with their root structures and trap nutrient-rich sediment during high water. Volunteers from the community participated in willow planting.

In the spring and summer 1999, three dams on the Naugatuck were completely removed and one dam was breached.  The full Naugatuck River Watershed Anadromous Fish Restoration Project is expected to significantly improve water quality and restore 32 miles of river, allowing passage for sea-run brown trout, American shad, alewives, blueback herring, and other aquatic species for the first time in over a century.  The project represents a remarkable commitment to river system restoration on a scale rarely attempted.

The original timber crib structure of the orphaned Chase Brass Dam was encased in concrete and presented a liability issue due to lack of proper maintenance.  The dam, which is part of a larger network of dams along the Naugatuck River, was removed to the bedrock in August 2004 to provide access to historic spawning habitat for several migratory fish species and improve water quality.
This structure was removed as part of a larger restoration effort on the Eight Mile River and opened the remaining historical habitat to fish and restore natural riverine functions of the river.

The dam owner, tired of the liability associated with a deteriorating dam and looking to turn a muck-filled pond back into a gently flowing stream, was supportive of the restoration project and the opportunity to partner with local and national groups to ensure its success. The dam's removal is restoring access to more than 16 miles of upstream riverine habitat within the Salmon River Watershed, reconnecting the river for juvenile Atlantic salmon, American eel, and native resident riverine species such as brook trout.

Description: The Spoonville Dam was partially breached in 1955 flooding, but remained a barrier to fish and a safety hazard. The 30-foot thick concrete structure was removed to enhance public safety and increase connectivity for diadromous fish.
The Ed Bills Pond dam is the third removal in the Eightmile River Watershed. The dam removal restores upstream access for migratory fish and 5 acres of river, wetland and floodplain habitat.
The Griswold Dam removal is the third barrier removal on the Moosup River as part of a partnership with CT DEEP and NRCS to restore the Moosup River.

The Hyde Pond Dam Removal was completed on Whitford Brook, a tributary of the Mystic River. It restored fish passage to 4.1 stream miles and habitat for alewife, blueback herring and American eel (candidate species under the Endangered Species Act), and mitigated flooding risk downstream of the dam.

The Pond Lily Dam Removal project increases capacity of the local coastal riverine habitat to withstand storms by eliminating the hazard of Pond Lily Dam's likely failure and restores a federal public asset by promoting migratory fish passage of federally protected species. The project eliminates threat of a catastrophic dam breach during future flooding. In total, approximately 2.6 miles of the West River and 76 acres of Konold's Pond habitat are being re-opened to migratory fish, including herring, eel and shad.

A 5' high earth and stone dam blocked the passage of migratory fish. The 80' long and 12' wide dam also served as an unimproved road, with a concrete slab over the spillway. Zemko Dam was the last remaining obstruction to fish passage on the East Branch Eightmile River. Complete removal of Zemko Dam, the last man-made obstruction on the East Branch Eightmile River, allows migratory fish to access their full historic range within this system.  In addition to improving fish passage, removal of the dam restores the river’s natural structure and flow, a key element of a watershed’s overall health, and will eliminate the potential for dam failure in the future. The property where the dam once stood has since been purchased by The Nature Conservancy and is therefore protected from future development. The Eightmile River was also recently designated by Congress as a Wild & Scenic River, which provides additional protection at the federal level.  This stone, concrete and earthen dam was removed in stages, and stream flow was diverted during the removal process.

The Karp Family Dam was associated with a former campground.  It was a concrete slab with upright piers that accepted stoplogs.  The family used to drop the stoplogs into the slots to impound the stream for swimming in the early summer and then remove the stoplogs and drain the pond in the fall.  The stoplogs are long gone and the river was no longer impounded, but the slab was over a foot high and blocked river herring runs.  The streambed is all bedrock (no sediment) and the habitat is in good shape. Furthermore, the piers collect large woody debris that can create an impoundment and a safety issue.  The project site was accessed rom the south bank, creating an earthen ramp to get equipment down to the river. Heavy equipment was utilized to batter the concrete structure into smaller pieces, remove the concrete demolition debris, and finally transport the material to a nearby State of Connecticut Wildlife Management Area where there was a large barn foundation hole that needed to be filled in for safety reasons. The last step of the project was restoration of the riverbanks. The dam was completely removed, down to bedrock and there was no sediment to deal with, keeping project costs low.

A pair of dams in the Quinnipiac River blocks the passage of diadromous fish. Carpenter's Dam in Meriden is 110' wide and 6' high; approximately 9 mile upstream, in Southington, lies the Clark Bothers Dam, 70' wide and 5' high. These dams are very old, with Clark Brothers possibly dating back to 1750. They are both in poor shape, and most importantly, no longer serve a purpose.  Both dams were completely removed to restore fish passage to historic spawning areas. Removal of these dams reconnected the Quinnipiac River, almost up to its headwaters at Dead Wood Swamp in Farmington, to the Long Island Sound. A 30-inch water pipe, owned by the City of Meriden but now abandoned, was also removed as part of this project, making this stretch of river passable to recreational boaters as well as fish.
A pair of dams in the Quinnipiac River blocks the passage of diadromous fish. Approximately 9 mile upstream of Carpenter's Dam, in Southington, lies the Clark Bothers Dam.

The Eagle and Phenix Dam was constructed in 1868 of granite stone and masonry to power the Eagle and Phenix textile mill. The newly free flowing river will help to restore natural flowing conditions to the Chattahoochee.
Original.Use: Power the defunct Eagle and Phenix textile Mill

Description: The objective of this Corps project is to breach these two dams in order to restore portions of the Fall Line shoal habitat.

The project site is located on the Middle Oconee River within the University of Georgia, Warnell School of Forestry and Natural Resources Whitehall Forest, City of Athens, Clarke County, Georgia. Approximately 520 feet downstream of White dam is the confluence of the Middle Oconee River and the North Oconee River. The objective of the proposed modification is to maximize environmental and ecosystem benefits while maintaining the historic value and structural integrity of the dam. Human safety and increased recreational use of the river are also important considerations. To accomplish this, a breach (including removing all of the concrete and natural stone wall and footing located between the two existing sluice gates) was implemented. This resulted in an 88.5 L.F. open section located slightly offset to the south of the center of the dam. The remaining section of dam, on either side of the abutments, will help protect the abutments from storm flows and help preserve the structural integrity and historic value of the dam.
Type_Material: Concrete gravity dam, with ogee section and two sluice gates/concrete and stone faces with rubble core

Owner: HI Dept Natural Resources; West Maui Land Co; Kahoma Land LLC

Description: According to an article in the Waterloo Cedar-Falls Courier, the Delaware County Conservation Board removed the Hopkinton Dam in 2004.

The Vernon Springs Dam was converted to rapids in August 2010, resulting in immediate reconnection of the upper Turkey River to the lake upstream and the river’s two main tributaries in Howard County for aquatic species. The structure eliminates re-circulating currents that contributed to past drownings while maintaining water elevation for a popular lake. Howard County Conservation Board initiated the project and raised funds. Minnesota stream restoration specialist Luther Aadland developed the concept design and conducted initial construction supervision; with Iowa DNR Rivers team members and DNR Engineering staff collaborating on final design and construction details. HCCB was awarded an FY2008 DNR low-head dam safety cost-share grant to construct a rock-arch rapids at a 20:1 slope below the existing dam and mill pond for safety and fish passage. Funds supporting the project included DNR Low-head Dam Public Hazard, U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Fish Passage, FEMA, and local business supporters.

The Klondike Dam to rapids conversion project was completed in May 2013. It involved removing the dam and construction a rapids that pools water to the same elevation of the dam to maintain water supply for a rural water system. The area is now safer, more accessible, and allows fish to pass upstream at both low and high water. Iowa DNR contributed $51,644 in state mitigation funds for design and construction.
Owner: South Dakota Department of Schools & Land/Iowa DNR

Description: It was a long winter of construction, but the Boone Waterworks Dam to Rapids Conversion project on the Des Moines River was completed in April of 2014. Five fatalities had been reported since 1971 at this dam.
Original.Use: Water supply for town of Boone

Description: This project converted a former low-head dam into a small rock-arch rapids in August 2014. Iowa DNR supplied $35,112 in dam mitigation grants, and DNR mitigation staff assisted with project management, design, and construction supervision. Citizen donations and city funds covered the remainder of the $70,000 total project cost.

This project had many partners, including  Iowa Department of Natural Resources ($200,000), Iowa Resource Enhancement and Protection Program ($100,000), Vision Iowa (Iowa River Enhancement Community and Attraction Tourism grant), and many others. Along with the dam removal, another big expense in the project went to moving a water main lower in the river bed. The City of Manchester pledged more than $600,000 to the project, and Delaware County contributed $50,000. Fundraising and private donations made up the difference in funding.  The whitewater park project is estimated to cost an additional $1.8 million.

This project converted the Quasqueton Dam into a rock arch rapids in late August 2014. The project is on the Wapsipinicon River Water Trail in Buchanan County. Iowa DNR low-head dam mitigation grants of $68,000 and technical / design support helped make this project possible. Formerly, this dam led to situations like this: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0DICS5CtnKA&feature=youtu.be.

Stream bank restoration immediately followed this dam removal, and has restored the river to a healthy habitat and improved navigation on a scenic part of the Shell Rock River for both paddlers and anglers.
Owner: Margaret Zeran, Floyd County Conservation Board

River: South Fork of Lake Fork Creek

Description: This removal was a collaborative effort that came as a result of the hydropower relicensing process this aging dam was undergoing.  Once complete, this restored stream will benefit native fish populations and recreational interests.

In September 2013, the Dutch Flat Dam was removed from a disused drinking water reservoir in Troy, ID.  Originally built in 1919, the reservoir had filled with silt by 1925. The removal of this dam gives access to 7 miles of spawning habitat for steelhead which migrate up the Columbia River each spring. The project was sponsored by the City of Troy with assistance from the Latah Soil and Water conservation District, and also included channel restoration and a fenced educational site adjacent to a recreational bike and walking trail.
River: West Fork of Little Bear Creek
Tributary to East Fork Wood River

Description: This dam was scheduled for removal in September 2002 to eliminate the public safety hazard presented by its poor condition and to allow for the passage of fish.  However, a review process carried out by the state and federal regulatory agencies delayed removal.  While the plans were being reviewed, storms created significant breaches that now enable fish to move past the dam. Because of these breaches, the removal was delayed throughout 2004 and the full dam was not removed until 2005.

This Kane County dam, the second of two removals, was taken out in order to reconnect Ferson Creek to Fox River and improve the health of upstream fish and mussel communities, thus preventing further loss of species. The removal of the upper and lower dams on Ferson Creek restores connectivity to six river miles.

This Kane County dam, the first of two removals, was taken out in order to reconnect Ferson Creek to Fox River and improve the health of upstream fish and mussel communities, thus preventing further loss of species. The removal of the upper and lower dams on Ferson Creek restores connectivity to six river miles.
This is one of three dams on the Des Plaines River that was removed for ecological benefits as well as public safety.
Owner: Forest Preserve District of Cook County

Description: This is one of three dams on the Des Plaines River that was removed for ecological benefits as well as public safety. The removal opened up ten miles of river habitat that will help upstream fish communities.

The Blackberry Creek Dam shared a cracked abutment with a county road and was removed as part of the Illinois Dam Safety Initiative. The project also connected fish in the Fox River to 32 miles of spawning and rearing habitat in Blackberry Creek  following removal in January 2013.
This restoration project on the Des Plaines River will eventually involve 7 total removals between Wisconsin and Joliet, Illinois.
This restoration project on the Des Plaines River will eventually involve 7 total removals between Wisconsin and Joliet, Illinois.

City_County: North of Mt. Carmel, Wabash County
Owner: US Army Corps, transfer to Boy Scouts of America
Type_Material: Stone masonry lock with white oak gates and a wood crib dam

Year_Built: Construction plans for the dam are dated 1948. However, other sources indicate that a dam has been in place at this location since 1918.
Type_Material: Concrete capped sheet piling dam and wingwalls with an 8" thick concrete apron extending 7'+/- downstream

Description: This project involved the removal of a low head dam (Oak Meadows) and a smaller bed control structure.  Additionally, the project included the installation of 9000 SF of substrate, 10 pools, and 4100 LF of naturalized streambank stabilization. Project also included the creation of 67 acres of riparian habitat, prairie, savanna, and woodlands.

The project included two dam removals-- Danville Dam and Ellsworth Park Dam. At Danville, the concrete dam spillway, west abutment and the two abandoned piers were removed.  Completion of the dam removal project removed a barrier of 175 stream miles upstream of Danville Dam and Ellsworth Park Dam in the Vermilion River basin, benefitting an extraordinarily high number of species in greatest need of conservation.  The dam was also considered a safety hazard.

The project included two dam removals-- Danville Dam and Ellsworth Park Dam. Completion of the dam removal project removed a barrier of 175 stream miles upstream of Danville Dam and Ellsworth Park Dam in the Vermilion River basin, benefitting an extraordinarily high number of species in greatest need of conservation.

Type_Material: Concrete wier against original timber crib

Description: Removal of the earthen dam and the two spillway structures.  Stream channel is being restored through the former mill pond area.

Dam_Name: Fox Farm Road Dam (Warsaw Water Supply Dam)

Description: This dam on the East Branch of the Housatonic River was breached in November 2000, doubling the available trout habitat.

The Billington Street Dam was removed in 2002.  Erosion at this over 200-year old earthen dam and deterioration of its fishway had blocked 
migration of alewives each spring.  Removal of this dam and restoration of Town Brook has restored the fisheries in an area where the pilgrims historically came to fish for alewife.

This dam was removed to benefit resident and migratory fish populations (Atlantic salmon).  This project is part of a larger restoration effort to restore Yokum Brook to free-flowing status with plans for breaching a downstream dam already in the works.
The Upper Cooks Canyon Dam served no current purpose and was removed because of the owner's liability concerns and restore habitat for resident species.  The dam was removed in June 2006.
Type_Material: Earthen berm dam with a concrete and wood control structure

Description: This dam was meant to promote trout spawning in a fishery created by the impoundment, as well as preserve water levels for a defunct cranberry operation.  As understanding of fish behavior and spawning habits has improved since those times, the dam was removed in fall 2006, because it inundated salter brook trout spawning habitat with excessive sediment.
Type_Material: Earthen berm dam with a wood control structure

Description: This dam was originally part of a now closed mill complex.  The dam was no longer used for its original purpose and blocked an Atlantic salmon restoration stream with high quality habitat for coldwater species.  Ballou Dam was removed by the Town of Becket and funded by a partnership developed by the Massachusetts Riverways Program.

The New Way Dam was removed as part of a larger restoration project spearheaded by the Massachusetts' Riverways program, the Trustees of Reservations, and others to restore one of the state's last remaining native sea-run brook trout populations.

Dam_Name: Eel River Headwaters Restoration (7 small dams)
Description: These earthen dams include wooden and concrete bog control structures. Located in Plymouth, the dams have controlled the operation of cranberry bogs since the late nineteenth century.
Type_Material: Earthen dams with concrete/wood control structures

Owner: Massachusetts Dept. of Fish and Game

Description: The removal of the Middle Flume of Red Brook restored 0.5 river miles. Reasons for the Middle Flume's removal include habitat enhancement, improvement of sediment transport, and elimination of erosion potential in the future. The removal of the concrete structure expanded spawning habitat for salter brook trout, improved floodplain connectivity, enhanced natural sediment transport, and facilitated fish passage for diadromous fish.

The removal of the Briggsville Dam in the town of Clarksburg, Massachusetts involved removing the dam, stabilizing the banks and planting trees, protecting an upstream bridge, and restoring over 30 miles of high quality headwater streams and exemplary trout habitat. Removing the dam will help its owner, Cascade School Supplies, avoid closing the facility, laying off employees, and leaving the community without one of its largest employers. Cascade School Supplies has been in business for 78 years and seasonally employs more than 150 people in Berkshire County, including their facility in Clarksburg, a small rural town in northwestern Massachusetts.

The Forge Pond Dam in Freetown breached during heavy storms in early February 2010, threatening nearby homes, and served as a wake-up call for dam owners statewide. The 300 year-old dam was one of the most unsafe dams in Massachusetts. The complete removal restored stream habitat for smelt and herring.

Original.Use: Power for a fly rod company

Description: In October of 2012, a series of three dams were removed on the Wellingsly Brook. These low-head, concrete dams ranged in size from 3 to 5 feet and were removed to restore habitat for sea-run native brook trout.

In October of 2012, a series of three dams were removed on the Wellingsly Brook. These low-head, concrete dams ranged in size from 3 to 5 feet and were removed to restore habitat for sea-run native brook trout.

In October of 2012, a series of three dams were removed on the Wellingsly Brook. These low-head, concrete dams ranged in size from 3 to 5 feet and were removed to restore habitat for sea-run native brook trout.

Removed in June of 2012, the Curtis Pond Dam removal is the first in a series of dam removals in the Ipswich River Watershed. This dam was removed to restore instream flow, migratory fish passage and improve river habitat. In particular, this removal will benefit river herring and American eel, two species that are being evaluated for the federal endangered species list. The dam has been deteriorating over the years, and by removing it, the owners (town of Danvers) will avoid future liability and upkeep.
This dam was removed as a part of the Thunder Brook Restoration Project to restore 2.4 miles of habitat for brook trout and other cold-water species, as well as increase public safety.
Two dams were removed as a part of the Phillipston Reservoir Dam.
River_Miles_Reported: 1 mile of headwaters stream above dam

Description: Two dams were removed as a part of the Phillipston Reservoir Dam.
River_Miles_Reported: 1 mile of headwaters stream above dam

Description: In October 2013, the Massachusetts Audubon assisted the Town of Pittsfield in removing the Gravesleigh Pond Dam as part of a wetland impacts mitigation project for the expansion of the municipal airport. The Mass Audubon Sanctuary runs onsite educational programs for the public and school groups, and will incorporate dam removal and river restoration as part of their program.

The Town of Plymouth removed this dam in November of 2013, replacing it with a bridge.  The dam is the third dam to be removed on the brook, which until 10 years ago, had 6 dams on it. The Town of Plymouth is also completing design plans for the next dam, Plymco Dam, which is the most upstream dam on the brook. The project restored spawning habitat for river herring and removed a public safety hazard.

In August 2013, the Whittenton Dam was removed as the second in a string of three dam removals from the Mill River in Taunton, MA. Concerns over dam owner liability, public safety, and fish passage prompted its removal.  A near failure in 2005 that would have caused catastrophic flooding resulted in the evacuation of 2000 people from downtown Taunton. The project also improved floodplain and river habitat for river herring, American eel, lamprey, and turtles.
Original.Use: Water power for textile mill and other mills prior
Mill dam and later cranberry bog water control

Year_Built: 1890 (but some previous dam was there earlier)

Description: The Millie Turner Pond Dam is located on the Nissitissit River and is part of property acquired by the Department of Fish and Game in 2010 for its significant ecological value.  Removal of this 10-foot-high dam would benefit coldwater fish and numerous rare species that use the considerable area of protected open space nearby.

This project restored fish passage to a historic herring run including hundreds of acres of prime spawning habitat. Besides the dam removal, the project also daylighted a 72-foot culverted portion of Town Brook.  Previous phases removed the Billington Street Dam, the Off-Billington Street Dam, and improved fish passage at the mouth of the Brook.

The Bleachery Dam was located at the mouth of the Rattlesnake Brook, which flows to the Assonet River, a tributary of the Taunton River in Freetown. The removal will support public safety, benefit migratory fish, reduce local flooding and improve water quality. This dam was owned by the City of Fall River for back-up water supply but never used for that purpose.
Type_Material: Earthern embankment/ stone masonry walls/concrete spillways

Description: Tack Factory Dam is the first dam on Third Herring Brook upstream from the tidal North River.
Type_Material: Earthern embankment/ stone masonry walls/concrete spillways

Description: This project removed a barrier to fish passage and restored more than 200 acres of cranberry bog to river/wetland ecosystem.
Dam was previously unknown as it was buried under sediments until a downstream dam was removed. Estimated to have been built between 1739-1820. May have been oldest recorded dam in Massachusetts.
Winchell Dam is one of five outdated former reservoir dams that the City of Westfield has identified for removal.
Removed the Balmoral Dam from the Shawsheen River in Andover, MA in conjuction with the removal of the upstream Marland Place Dam
Partner led project to remove a deteoriating privately owned dam and protect upstream infrastructure

Dam_Name: Charles River Mill Dam (Pearl Street Mill Dam)
Description: Town led project to remove obsolete and aging dam; project involved dredging to address mercury contamination in sediment

The removal of Coonamessett Lower Bog Dam is part of the first phase of a larger restoration project aiming to restore connectivity to 2.2 miles of river through two dam removals and culvert replacements.
Removal of three dams on Hamant Brook will restore cold-water habitat for native species, including brook trout.
Removal of three dams on Hamant Brook will restore cold-water habitat for native species, including brook trout.
Removal of three dams on Hamant Brook will restore cold-water habitat for native species, including brook trout.
Removed the Marland Place Dam on the Shawsheen River in Andover, MA in conjunction with the removal of the downstream Balmoral Dam.

Dam_Name: Mordecai Lincoln Road Pond Dam (Hunters Pond Dam)
Description: Town led project to remove obsolete and aging dam

Barstowe's Pond Dam was the first and only impediment to stream fishes between the Taunton River and the headwaters of the Cotley River. Barstowe's Pond Dam was an 8-ft tall wooden dam that provided no fish passage on a tributary to the Taunton River in Taunton, MA. It was the only complete obstruction on the Cotley River, and with no obstruction on the Taunton River. Removal of the dam opened miles of habitat for alewife and American eel.
Owner: Taunton Development Corporation & Mashpee Wampanoag Tribe

Description: This project removed the aging mill dam from the Mill River in Taunton, Massachusetts and increased the benefits of a restored river system while protecting human structures. The project opened up 30 miles of high-quality habitat for American eel and river herring, which are under consideration for federal listing. It also reduced the probability of flooding and eliminated the potential for catastrophic dam breaches posed by these obsolete dams.

This was the third dam removed on the Mill River in Taunton. The river restoration began with the near failure of the upstream Whitteton Dam in 2005, which raised awareness of dam safety issues in Massachusetts. Restoration on the Mill River in Taunton, Massachusetts reached a milestone in January. The West Britannia Dam was demolished. 13 years ago four dams in short series on the Mill River were all in poor or failing condition, and all blocking fish passage. Three dams have now been removed and one dam repaired with a fish ladder installed, opening access to important habitat for river herring in the Wild and Scenic Taunton River Watershed, and securing a safer community without failing infrastructure. The story is worth understanding. In 2005, when dam removal was still young in Massachusetts, the Whittendon Dam nearly failed catastrophically (it was national news) causing the evacuation of 2000 residents of the City of Taunton. This near failure kicked off a series of questions about state dam safety, eventually leading to an overhaul of state dam safety legislation/regulations in a case study and model that we still use today. American Rivers had significant staff time providing technical review and fundraising support and money (through our former NOAA-Restoration grants) in much of this work.

The Roberts Meadow Upper Reservoir Dam removal restored habitat for cold water species. The 135 year old dam was no longer in use and was in need of repair. The dam was removed in three stages over the course of the summer in order to allow for natural redistribution of sediment within the 8 acre impoundment.

Removed in October of 2005, the Octoraro Rubble Dam previously was the only blockage on Octoraro Creek, a tributary of the Susquehanna River just below the Pennsylvania line in Maryland. The dam was blocking an estimated annual run of 600,000 blueback herring, as well as hickory shad, from entering the creek's 19 miles of high quality habitat.  The removal cleared the way for these fish to utilize upstream spawning grounds.

The PPG Dam, once owned by the Pittsburg Plate & Glass company and now by Allegany County, was originally built to impound water for a pumping station that pumped river water for industrial uses. At the time of its removal in fall 2007, it no longer served a purpose. The dam impounded half a mile of the Potomac River and was removed both to reduce a navigational hazard, thus increasing boating opportunities, and to promote easier passage of American eel.
Original.Use: Originally built to back up water for a pumping station.
Water supply for the City of Hagerstown

Description: Built around 1940, Puckum Branch Dam was an earthen dam with a pipe culvert.  It was built to accommodate a logging road and was removed to allow for fish passage and stream restoration.  Alewife, blueback herring and perch are among the fish species expected to benefit most significantly from the removal.  Removal of Puckum Branch Dam occurred in January 2007.

The Simkins Dam, which originally powered a textile mill, was removed in 2010 to restore habitat for American eel, alewife, blueback herring and American shad. In addition to restoring 20 miles of habitat for these migratory species, the removal of the Simkins Dam is anticipated to increase oxygenation and improve water quality, restore the natural flow of sediment, and allow for greater navigability for boaters, tubers with the decreased safety hazards. This project was partially funded by an American Recovery and Reinvestment Act (ARRA) grant from the NOAA Restoration Center.

The Union Dam was built in 1900 for the purposes of powering a textile mill. Hurricane Agnes breached the dam in 1972. Since then, it exacerbated erosion and created velocity barriers for fish passage. The removal restored 23 miles of the river for migratory fish and eliminated a safety hazard for boaters and other users.

Original.Use: Water supply for City of Frederick

Description: The Whitehall Dam was removed in August of 2011 providing passage to wild reproducing brown trout and alleviating thermal pollution impacts.  Hurricane Irene and Tropical Strom Lee caused significant damage to the project site immediately after removal. Fortunately the National Resources Conservation Service (NRCS) secured last-minute funding to repair the structures and regrade the banks.

This project involved removing a failing sheet-pile dam and restoring 600 ft of the river with a series of weirs and pools to restore fish passage to the St. Martin River located in Bishopville, Maryland, thereby allowing access to about 7 miles of spawning and nursery habitat for both anadromous and catadromous fish.

AR partnered with Maryland DNR, USFWS, and the Town of Centreville to remove the Centreville Dam on Gravel Run, improving connectivity for aquatic species and restoring quality habitat upstream. The Centreville Dam consisted of a concrete and stone structure approximately five-feet tall and 10-feet long. This obsolete dam blocked nearly 13 miles of habitat for alewife, blueback herring, American eel, and yellow and white perch. By restoring access to historic spawning habitat, these target species have a greater chance of survival and propagation.

The Bloede Dam removal is the linchpin of a larger plan— including removal of the Union and Simkins dams in 2010— to restore more than 65 miles of spawning habitat for blueback herring, alewife, American shad, hickory shad, and more than 183 miles for American eel in the Patapsco River watershed. Originally built in the early 1900s to supply electrical power to the cities of Catonsville in Baltimore County and Ellicott City in Howard County, the 34-foot high by 220-foot long dam was owned by the Maryland Department of Natural Resources. At the time of demolition, it served no functional purpose, but caused numerous injuries and deaths, with at least nine dam-related deaths since the 1980s.
The Edwards Dam was removed through a voluntary settlement agreement over the summer and fall of 1999.  It was completed in October 1999 under budget and ahead of schedule.

The Canaan Lake Outlet Dam was used by the lumber industry for log drives from the 1800s through the 1960s.  The dam, which was largely deteriorated prior to its removal in the summer of 1999, impeded the passage of migratory fish (including Atlantic salmon) to upstream spawning habitat.

The Brownville Dam, which was partially breached prior to its removal in August 1999, was the only impediment to adult salmon migration on the Pleasant River.  Now with the dam gone, there is an opportunity to develop a recreational area at this site, in addition to the improved conditions for migratory fish.

Archer's Mill Dam was over 100 years old and was a barrier to migrating fish prior to its removal in September 1999.  The removal-and associated dredging to remove lumber, bark, sawdust and debris that accumulated behind the dam-will improve stream habitat and water quality on Stetson Stream.

A 1996 flood extensively damaged this hydropower dam and its fish ladder preventing the facility from producing power or passing fish without first undergoing expensive repairs.  Instead the owners decided to remove the structure, which occurred in fall 2002.  Dam removal is expected to restore the lower portion of the Presumpscot, creating habitat for striped bass, smelt, river herring, and American eel and opening passage for other migratory fish.  This was a Coastal America project, part of an overall effort in the Northeast to restore anadromous fisheries migration corridors and restore salt marshes and wetlands throughout our estuaries.  The Maine Departments of Environmental Protection and Marine Resources, and the Coastal Conservation Association, spearheaded the removal of the Smelt Hill dam, with significant funding and engineering assistance from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, and other assistance from local interests.  The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the Maine Department of Environmental Protection worked with numerous local interests to accomplish this project.

The dam removal is one part of a collaborative effort to restore fish passage to the St. George River and maintain desirable water levels in Sennebec Pond.  The former hydro dam was badly deteriorated, and its owners determined that the cheapest way to restore fish passage and maintain lake levels was to remove the dam and build a 30-inch high rock ramp fishway at the natural outlet of the pond.
The dam was removed as part of a license surrender by Madison Electric Works, the dam's owner.

The removal of the West Winterport Dam from the North Branch of Marsh Stream opened up more than 20 miles of river and stream habitat for a variety of native sea-run fish species, Atlantic salmon, sea-run brook trout, alewives, blueback herring, sea lamprey, American shad, and American eel. Dam removal eliminated a 4.5- mile long impoundment and restored this section of the river to its natural conditions. The North Branch of Marsh Stream has returned to being a complex riverine ecosystem with various pools and riffle/run habitat with large boulders and a mix of sand, gravel, and cobble substrate. A large amount of large woody debris was also uncovered within thestream channel following the removal of the impoundment. The project is also expected to increase recreational fishing opportunities for brook trout.

Lower Montsweag Brook Dam acted as a complete barrier to fish passage. The goal of the project was to restore native and diadromous fisheries resources in the lower watershed though removal of the dam, which was completed in early November 2010. Originally erected as an emergency water source for the Maine Yankee Atomic Plant, the dam is no longer in use because the plant is closed. Fish passage was also restored to 20 acres of impoundment, 3 acres of stream, and 17 acres of wetlands. It also reconnected the Brook with 200 acres of restored tidal marsh downstream. Another goal of the project is to leverage long-term monitoring of the brook for hands-on education and field science opportunities for local students.
River_Miles_Reported: 3 acres stream, 17 acres of wetland, 200 acres marsh

Description: Removal of the dam in 2012 restored habitat for Atlantic salmon, shad and river herring. Additionally, the removal will provide numerous community benefits including paddling and fishing. The Great Works Dam was removed as part of a larger restoration project for the Penobscot River that will eventually open up 1,000 miles of fish habitat.

The Chandler Brook in Pownal, Maine is running free for the first time since 1796 after the July 2013 removal of the Randal Mill Dam. Originally used as a sawmill, the dam was removed after the private owner learned about the benefits of the proposed removal of two dams on the Royal River in the Town of Yarmouth. The removal was part of the Sebago Trout Unlimited and Casco Bay Estuary Project and will restore three miles of brook trout habitat.
Year_Built: 1796 (original dam at site at this time)

Description: In July 2013, the Sebago Chapter of Trout Unlimited in partnership with Mollyockett Chapter and the Casco Bay Estuary Partnership removed this dam near Waterford Maine on Swett Brook, a tributary of the Crooked River.

The removal of the Veazie Dam on the Penobscot River kicked off to much excited in July 2013. This concrete buttress style hydropower dam was constructed in 1913, but dams had been recorded on the site since at least the 1830’s. Atlantic salmon and other sea run fish will have access to 1000 miles of migratory habitat when combined with the removal of Great Works and passage being planned at the Howland Dam upstream.

The East Machias Dam was abandoned by Bangor Hydro due to its lack of adequate power generation in 1962 and subsequently sold to the Town of East Machias for $1.The town considered reconstructing the dam but found this was not feasible, and although the dam had a fishway included at the time of its construction, it was ineffective at passing fish. This dam also made it impossible for recreational use, including canoeing. Recognizing these impacts, in 1996, the Downeast Salmon Federation, a local salmon conservation organization, approached the Town of East Machias to assist the town in its removal.
This remnant dam was removed from the Sunday River by USFWS, Trout Unlimited, Project SHARE, and Maine Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife.
Removal of the dam is part of a multi-phased effort of removals and fishways to restore alewife to China Lake.

Type_Material: Gravity masonry structure with concrete overlays

Owner: Owned by the Smyrna Milling Company, the dam was sold to Consumers Power, then to Otisco Township in 1956. The Township deeded the dam to DNR in 1971 under the condition that it be removed at state expense and $40,000 was appropriated for this purpose.

Dam_Name: Air Force Dam (Silver Lead Creek Dam)

Description: This dam was removed by Michigan DNR Fisheries Division Construction Crew in August 2000.
Owner: Michigan Dept Natural Resources Fisheries Division

Description: This dam was a safety hazard, and its removal has opened up nearly 120 miles of free flowing reaches, one of the longest reaches of river in Michigan.  The removal of Big Rapids Dam has made this stretch of river safer for canoeing and swimming and more aesthetically pleasing.  Follow the dam removal, the community constructed a riverwalk to draw more people to the river.

The dam was originally used to divert water to a mill and was in a state of disrepair. The decision to remove the dam was aided by the fact that the structure was no longer serving a purpose, and removal costs ($78,000) were much less than estimated costs to repair (>$200,000).

This dam removal, which was conducted in stages, began in 2000, and was done in conjunction with road crossing (snowmobile trail) replacement aimed at restoring fish passage.  The removal was completed in 2003 by the Road Commission.  Funding for this project was contributed by the USDA Forest Service, the Bear Creek Watershed Council, and Conservation Resource Alliance.

The removal of Sturgeon Dam is part of an agreement made by We Energies, federal and state resource agencies, and the Michigan Hydropower Reform Coalition in 1996.  The removal of this structure occured in three phases over a four to five year time period and opened spawning habitat for lake sturgeon.  Removing the dam in stages allowed for the reservoir and sediment transport to stabilize and reduce fish and wildlife impacts.

Built near the turn of the century and used to provide cooling water for turbines of a public water facility, the dam was removed to allow for natural river function and fish passage and also to return the degraded stream back to a viable river within the City of Charlotte's park system.  The project also included remeandering a a mile-long section of river (previoulsy a straight ditch).

Originally constructed by Consumers Energy to maintain the water level for a cooling water intake, this dam no longer served its purpose.  Consumers Energy agreed to work with the Michigan DNR toward removal to restore fish passage and improve water quality and stream habitat in the vicinity.

Owner: Marquette Board of Power and Light

Description: This dam impounded an 85 acre pond.   The community chose a partial removal in order to promote healthy stream ecosystem function by restoring free movement of aquatic organisms and restoring water quality to nearly pre-dam conditions while managing instream sediments. A partial removal also retains a local point of interest that is important to the community.

The Hersey Dam was removed in September 2006 in order to restore this premier coldwater trout stream.  Removing the dam and sediment accumulated behind it helped to restore the river's natural flow and water temperature, improve fish habitat, and increase recreational opportunities.

In order to maintain water levels in the impoundment and still allow for the passage of fish, approximately 4-foot of head of the dam was removed and a series of three rock weirs were built below the dam to construct rapids that will allow all fish species to have unimpeded fish passage.

Original.Use: Abandoned dam and culvert on this trout stream were removed to restore fish passage.

Description: This dam had fallen out of use and into disrepair.

The structure failed and was removed to alleviate concerns over safety and liability. The removal, which restored 18 river miles, has improved safety, recreational use of the river, fish passage,  aquatic habitats, and the river's aesthetic appeal.

Removal of the Nashville Dam restores access to 60 miles of habitat for aquatic species and opened additional access to park land. A robust monitoring plan was implemented by a number of local partners to assess the success of this restoration project.

The Clinton River Watershed Council, Michigan Department of Natural Resources, and Oakland University partnered to remove the Paint Creek Dam using funding awarded through the Great Lakes Restoration Initiative. The removal restored fish passage to 7.25 miles of Paint Creek, the only coldwater stream and trout fishery in Southeast Michigan.

The Brown Bridge Dam on the Boardman River was removed in August of 2012, the first in a series of 3 dam removals along the river. The dam was decommissioned in 1996 after it was determined it was no longer economically feasible to produce power on the Boardman River. Removal of all 3 dams will eventually restore 18 miles of the river, reconnecting the river to Grand Traverse Bay and will also reconnect the river to an additional 160 miles of rivers and tributaries. This is the largest river restoration project undertaken in Michigan’s history.

The dam was originally built in the 1850s to power a saw mill, but was considered an unsightly public safety hazard. Its removal restores connectivity to 12 miles of the Cass River, and an additional 41 miles when combined with the planned 2014 removal of Frankenmuth Dam.
This dam was breached in floods in 1986, and the remnants were removed in 2014.
The dam material at this site was used to construct a snake hibernaculum.

This project restored the Paw Paw River by removing both the spillway and diversion dams located just east of M-140 at Watervliet.  After removal, the river channel and banks were restored to improve fish habitat and water quality. The Watervliet Dam was the only obstruction on the Paw Paw River from Lake Michigan to the Maple Lake dam in Paw Paw Village its removal opened over 100 miles of river and stream habitat.

This project restored the Paw Paw River by removing both the spillway and diversion dams located just east of M-140 at Watervliet.  After removal, the river channel and banks were restored to improve fish habitat and water quality. The Watervliet Dam was the only obstruction on the Paw Paw River from Lake Michigan to the Maple Lake dam in Paw Paw Village its removal opened over 100 miles of river and stream habitat.

The City of Troy, Michigan removed the Aquatic Center Pond Dam, replaced two failed metal culverts with concrete box culverts, and reestablished over three acres of native riparian vegetation buffer in the Red Run drainage.
Removal of private dam to return stream to free-flowing condition. Old dam structure was replaced with a large arch culvert to preserve private driveway access.

Dam_Name: Song of the Morning Ranch Dam (Golden Lotus Dam; Lansing Club Dam)

Owner: MI Dept Natural Resources Fisheries Division
MI Dept Natural Resources Fisheries Division
MI Dept Natural Resources Fisheries Division

Description: Removed old low head dam and created off channel pond and kayak route using Natural Resources Trust funds for recreational development.

The dam demolition consists of the removal of the arch dam structure, wing walls, and entire box culvert to the existing 84 inches x 120 inches corrugated metal pipe (CMP) culvert. The earth fill outside the box culvert is re-graded to a 1:3 (v:h) slope and stabilized with rip rap. The existing CMP culvert is extended to a minimum of 12 feet in order to maintain the proposed 1:3 (v:h) slope from Danvers Drive. This restores the flow of Pebble Creek through the existing CMP culvert. The existing culvert under Danvers Creek serves as downstream grade control for the restored stream channel.

The project will remove the dam and restore fish passage. In addition to the removal of the dam the project removes an instream island downstream of the dam and reconstructs a more stable single flow channel with bankfull benches, installs an engineered riffle/boulder cascade to protect existing infrastructure and facilitate fish passage, and provides for bank stabilization.

The Boardman River Dam removal is part of a larger restoration effort to address four barriers along the Boardman River in Michigan. This removal not only removed an impediment to fish passage, but also improved a river crossing for local residents. Previously, the Brown Bridge Dam was removed in 2013, and plans are in place to remove Sabin Dam and modify Union Street Dam in the near future. The largest river restoration project in Michigan’s history, collectively the project will restore more than two river miles of native coldwater fisheries habitat, more than 250 acres of wetlands and nearly 60 acres of upland habitat.

Owner: Michigan Dept Natural Resources Wildlife Division
Michigan Dept Natural Resources Wildlife Division
Michigan Dept Natural Resources Wildlife Division
Michigan Dept Natural Resources Park & Recreation Division

Description: When fully implemented, the Boardman River Dams Ecosystem Restoration Project  will reconnect over 160 miles of free-flowing, cold-water stream and restore hundreds of acres of wetland and upland habitat.  It is one of the most comprehensive dam removal and restoration projects in Michigan’s history and one of the largest such projects in the Great Lakes Basin. The Sabin Dam is the last of three dams on the Boardman River to be removed. The project included numerous stakeholders and work to provide full valley bottom restoration, including channel, floodplain and upland habitat restoration.
Owner: Grand Traverse County (originally Traverse City Light and Power)

Description: Significant sediment stabilization and installation of grade controls occurred following removal.
This dam partially failed in 1997, and was removed and replaced with rock arch rapids in 1999.

Dam_Name: Otter Tail Power Steam Plant Dam
Description: Originally, this project was not able to be completed as designed, due to lack of appropriate equipment.  In 2005, two riffles were built at 200 and 330 feet downstream of the dam crest to raise tail-water and reduce head-loss through the rapids at the dam. Two boulder weirs were also added at 20 and 40 feet downstream of the dam crest to equalize head-loss through each weir. Following these modifications, smallmouth bass were observed passing through the site.

In January 2013, Xcel Energy removed its 107 year old dam at Minnesota Falls on the Minnesota River, just downstream of Granite Falls. The dam was a safety hazard that had not produced hydropower for decades.
This project involved dam removal and rock rapid installation.
This project involved dam removal and rock rapid installation.
This project involved dam removal and rock rapid installation.
Dam abutments were historically significant and were left in place. Three boulder weirs were built for grade control and habitat. The river I now open to the headwaters.
This project involved dam removal and rock rapid installation.
City_County: Grand Forks, ND; East Grand Forks, MN
River_Miles_Reported: main stem Red River only 2 dams left

This project removed an old cement vertical 6 ft weir dam and replaced it with 6 rock riffles spaced over 2,000 ft for easier fish passage. Minnesota DOT aimed to make up the elevation difference for the one mile of stream fall lost when they built the interstate and cut off a one mile loop of the river that went south of the interstate to avoid building a bridge.

Modification/Partial removal and rock-arch-rapids. These four concrete dams were installed on the Sand Hill River as part of a flood control project conducted by the Army Corps of Engineers in the 1950s. The obstructions took their toll on fish populations by preventing fish migrations, a problem that contributed to wiping out lake sturgeon from the Red River Basin and reduced fishing opportunities in many streams. This project aimed to restore fish passage from the Red River to 50 miles of quality upstream Lake Sturgeon and Walleye habitats in the Sand Hill River by modifying four structures which currently block access.

Modification/Partial removal and rock-arch-rapids. These four concrete dams were installed on the Sand Hill River as part of a flood control project conducted by the Army Corps of Engineers in the 1950s. The obstructions took their toll on fish populations by preventing fish migrations, a problem that contributed to wiping out lake sturgeon from the Red River Basin and reduced fishing opportunities in many streams. This project aimed to restore fish passage from the Red River to 50 miles of quality upstream Lake Sturgeon and Walleye habitats in the Sand Hill River by modifying four structures which currently block access.

The community wanted to retain the pool level and downstream fishing hole.  The rapids was built to the same elevation as the dam and entirely of loose rock and aggregate with no sheet piling or artificial leakage barrier.  The river is subject to low flows so voids in the rock base were filled with 
6” and smaller aggregate to minimize leakage.  Discharge measurements taken during construction were 132.2 cfs at the crest of the rapids and 135.0 cfs at a river cross-section 433 feet downstream 
indicating minimal leakage since measurement error was ±2.7 cfs.  It is anticipated that the rapids will be further sealed by organic matter and sediment carried by the river.
River: West Branch Lac qui Parle River

Description: Removed a failed concrete dam and earthen dike in conjunction with rock riffle construction and historic channel reconnection.
River_Miles_Reported: 1/3 mile of stream  and 2628 acres of lake

Description: Dam removed from under bridge near Whitney Park, but bridge left in place

The Pelican Lake Dam project involved the transformation of a dam into a fish friendly culvert. There is a local road on the crest of the dam. The original spillway culvert for the dam was in very poor condition. The homeowners around the lake were not interested in keeping the lake so the original spillway was removed and a new 5’ diameter culvert was installed at the original streambed elevation thereby having the remaining embankment function as a roadway embankment. There is no water pooled upstream of the embankment.
The Stimson Dam (AKA Bonner Dam) was removed as part of the Federal Superfund cleanup of the Milltown Dam site.

This large, privately owned dam was removed as part of a larger effort to remove tons of sediment contaminated with heavy metals from behind this crumbling dam.  Removal of the dam and contaminated sediment eliminated the risk of all of the arsenic and other heavy metals being swept downstream if the dam breached. The removal also reconnected the Clark Fork and Blackfoot Rivers.

This dam impounded a mine tailings pond on Helena National Forest. The U.S. Forest Service partnered with Montana Department of Environmental Quality to manage the reclamation and remediation of the tailings and dam removal. The lead and zinc mine tailings date back to the World War II-era. This $40 million project was funded through a settlement between the state and former mine owner Asarco. In 1975, this dam blew out, sending 200,000 cubic yards of tailings downstream, devastating fish and other river species.

The Egge Diversion Dam on the Musselshell River near Lavina, Montana was severely damaged by the floods of 2011. Additionally, the river eroded around the diversion dam creating a new channel about 160 feet wide in an irrigated field. The irrigator and adjacent landowners felt removal of the dam with conversion to pumps and pivots and restoration of the bank would be mutually beneficial and maintain aquatic connectivity.
The removal of Rains Mill Dam in December 1999, in which the US Marine Corps assisted using plastic explosives, has had significant environmental benefits.

This dam was a 28 feet thick, hollow-concrete structure with 3 radial sluice gates used to regulate water levels.  It was built in the early 1970s as part of park revitalization effort and to create a pond for paddleboats and other recreation as part of a 'riverwalk'.  Removal of the structure is part of an overall restoration plan for Freedom Park and Little Sugar Creek.

A company named Restoration Systems purchased this dam for the purpose of mitigation credits.  Its removal opens about 39 miles of spawning habitat and there are already reports of shad migrating past the former dam.

This was a joint project of the Service’s Wadmalaw Island Fish and Wildlife Conservation Office and the Raleigh Ecological Service Office.  State partners include the North Carolina Division of Marine Fisheries, the North Carolina Wildlife Resources Commission and the North Carolina Division of Water Resources. The project also entailed removal of a semi-natural log jam that has developed immediately upstream of the mill dam. Economic benefits of the dam removal are increased commercial and recreational harvest of American shad, river herring, and striped bass.
This dam ceased generating power in 1999, and FERC issued a license exemption in 2001.

This dam's removal restored 44 river miles and provided additional habitiat for olive darter, sharphead darter, and Appalachian elktoe mussel. The dam removal has also played a role in improving access to the river and recreational opportunities. Spruce Pine, the dam's location, was named a Heritage Trout Water City by the state of North Carolina. Additionally, Toe River Valley Watch has begun work on a paddling trail.

The Altapass Dam, a privately-owned earthen dam in the French Broad River basin, was removed in the summer of 2010 through a partnership between the owners, the Blue Ridge Resource Conservation and Development Council, and the US Fish and Wildlife Service. The dam removal was combined with additional stream restoration and re- planting along the banks. It is expected to improve native brook trout habitat in the creek, allow for passage upstream, and improve water quality by restoring natural temperatures and re-oxygenating the water.
Owner: Blue Ridge Resource Conservation and Dev. Council; USFWS

Description: Progress Energy removed this large, obsolete dam in the spring of 2010 to improve public safety and restore the creek, which feeds into the Cape Fear River. The dam had outlived its purpose of supplying water to a power generation facility and was serving as a hazard for hunters, hikers, and others passing through on state game land. The removal was combined with restoration of two tributaries and re-planting of stream banks. It is expected to benefit resident fish and insects, which in turn will support wildlife populations in the game land.

The Dillsboro Dam, a hydropower dam owned by Duke Energy, was removed in 2010 as part a FERC relicensing agreement. The removal of this concrete dam will restore critical habitat for aquatic species in the Tuckasegee River, including the endangered Appalachian Elktoe Mussel. In addition to the ecological benefits, the removal has uncovered new whitewater for the paddlers in the region.
This is the first in a four part dam removal series in the Little River Watershed.

River_Miles_Reported: 14.6 miles of potential spawning habitat for fish on the main stem of the river and an overall total of 189 river miles

Owner: Jessie Cox Smitherman built the dam to power cotton yarn mill for Smitherman Cotton Mill. The Capel family donated the dam to the town of Troy a few years prior to the removal.

Description: The removal of this structure benefits fish passage and allows for safer travel on the Haw River Paddle Trail.
Owner: John Armstrong built the Upper Swepsonville Dam in 1790 to power his grist and sawmills; the Town of Swepsonville owned this dam at the time of its removal

Description: The Lower Big Hungry Dam was built atop a bedrock cascade in a narrow location in the valley on the Big Hungry River.  The dam had been out of operation for many decades when aquired by NCWRC through a land purchase from Duke Power in the mid to late 1980's.  The structure was in disrepair and a safety liability when aquired. The structure also impaired physical and biological processes within the watershed.  It is the downstream dam of a set of 2 dams; the upper dam is < 1 mi upstream and will likely be removed in the next 2 years.

The Blue Ridge Resource Conservation & Development Council and the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service were the project leads. American Rivers is proud to have supported this successful dam removal through technical assistance.
This project included the full removal of 3 remnant dams with the largest of the three being a 2-ft high, 270-ft long Granite Mill dam.
This project included the full removal of 3 remnant dams, including the largest Granite Mill Dam.
This project included the full removal of 3 remnant dams, including the largest Granite Mill Dam.
Earthen pond dam and water control structure removed.  200 ft of stream channel restored.

The Shuford Mill Dam, formerly a 35-foot tall, 275-foot wide masonry and concrete dam on the Henry Fork River in Brookford, North Carolina, was constructed in the late 1800s to power an adjacent textile mill, but stopped being maintained years ago after the mill closed and the dam no longer served a purpose. The dam removal eliminates the public safety risk of an unmaintained dam, improves the local community’s ability to recreate safely on the Henry Fork River, and restores 10 miles of the Henry Fork River for connectivity of aquatic habitat for fish and mussel species. This project is an excellent example of partnership where American Rivers worked with the Carolina Land and Lakes Resource Conservation and Development Council, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and others to remove an old and outdated dam.

The objective for this project is to restore the watershed to conditions that are more suitable to the native fish and aquatic salamander populations.  The Santeetlah Creek fish barrier was constructed in the 1960’s to prevent native fish (known as “rough fish”) from swimming upstream into Santeetlah Creek.  The creek was then poisoned upstream of the barrier to remove the native fish and subsequently restocked with non-native rainbow and brown trout (also in the 1960’s).  In the 1980’s, the USFS attempted to construct a fish ladder on the barrier to provide passage for trout.  Santeetlah Creek is too warm at this elevation to support the native brook trout.
Dam removal to restore 32,590 lf of the Neuse River in Wake County and create the Milburnie Dam Mitigation Bank

Hoosier Dam is a 94-year-old concrete buttress dam with an attached hydroelectric powerhouse. The hydroelectric facility at Hoosier Dam contains three turbines that were operated until 2014. In August 2016, the dam was proposed for removal as part of an awarded National Fish and Wildlife Foundation grant to restore the Rocky River from its currently impounded state back to a free flowing (lotic) state. The removal of the Hoosier Dam will open up 18,138 linear feet of habitat between two critical habitat areas for the endangered Cape Fear shiner. Unique Places is working hand in hand with multiple sate and federal regulatory agencies to accomplish this effort.
Type_Material: Primarily concrete w/stone and mortar section

Description: The McGoldrick Paper Company agreed to remove the dam to allow passage of migratory fish to upstream spawning habitat.  Because the site has historical value, photo documentation, biographies, and interpretive signage were developed as part of the restoration effort.

The dam was removed due to safety concerns and as part of a broader restoration effort on the Ashuelot River.  Removal of this dam opened additional spawning habitat for American shad, river herring, American eel, and Atlantic salmon, and is expected to benefit the dwarf wedge mussel, a federal endangered species indigenous to the Ashuelot River.
The dam was removed to eliminate dam safety concerns and as part of one of New Hampshire's larger river restoration efforts.

Since the early 1980's, this dam had not served any purpose.  Because the site, which was owned by the Town of Henniker, is heavily contaminated, it is considered a Brownfield by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and thus requires emergency action.  The project restored 15 miles of Contoocook River from Hillsborough to Hopkinton to free-flowing condition, which is expected to benefit juvenile Atlantic salmon, American eel, and trout.

This high-hazard, privately-owned dam was partially breached in an emergency action in December 2003.  Then, a 45-foot wide section of the 18-foot high dam was removed to eliminate the public safety hazard.  The project also reconnected 12 miles of the Tioga River and tributaries, and is expected to benefit trout, darters and additional resident fish species.

These two dams were removed in 2005, with final inspection occurring in June 2006.  The removal was part of a mitigation package for the Skyhaven Airport project.  This restoration includes the transfer of 184 acres of land to the Society for the Protection of New Hampshire Forests.

These two dams were removed in 2005, with final inspection occurring in June 2006.  The removal was part of a mitigation package for the Skyhaven Airport project.  This restoration includes the transfer of 184 acres of land to the Society for the Protection of New Hampshire Forests.

This dam was structurally deficient and in need of repairs. The dam's owner determined it was more beneficial to remove the dam, restoring the river and eliminating safety and liability concerns. The dam was removed in September 2008 and restored some 14 miles of habitat for migratory fish.

The City of Manchester, the New Hampshire Department of Environmental Services, and other partners worked together to remove the outdated Maxwell Pond Dam and restore eight miles of free-flowing river for alewife, blueback herring, Atlantic salmon, and other migratory fish. This project also improved overall water quality and was instrumental in getting Black Brook (a tributary of the Merrimack River) removed from the state's 'impaired waters' list with the brook meeting designated uses of Aquatic Life Use Support within 6 months of dam removal.
Owner: The City of Manchester, NH owns the dam.  The dam was originally constructed to create Maxwell Pond on Black Brook in 1900 for the purpose of ice harvesting.
Type_Material: Concrete and cut-stone/field stone dam with uncontrolled spillway and gate.

Owner: New Hampshire Fish and Game Department

Description: The Homestead Woolen Mills Dam had been in disrepair for several years. The high cost to repair the dam, coupled with the desire to restore the free-flowing river, prompted the dam owner, Homestead Woolen Mill, Inc., to pursue removal as an option for meeting dam safety requirements. The dam is immediately downstream from the historic Thompson Covered Bridge. By opening up about 25 miles of river habitat, this project not only restored fish passage, but also improved natural flows and aquatic habitat for a host of freshwater biodiversity in the ecologically significant Ashuelot River.
This dam was removed to mitigate wetland impacts from a development.

Removed in 2012, this dam was built between 1900 and 1915 by the Abbott family for scenic and recreation purposes. It was removed to improve safety and reduce liability, as well as to provide better habitat for resident aquatic species and amphibians. The removal will restore almost one mile of this tributary to a free flowing system.
River: Unnamed Stream - tributary to Souhegan River
Owner: Girl Scouts of the Green and White Mountains
Original.Use: Originally built by Abbott family likely for scenic and recreation.  More current use was for recreation.

Description: The dam was removed for safety and liability purposes, as well as providing a better habitat for aquatic species and amphibians.
Original.Use: Water supply for the Benjamin Chase Mill (downstream)
River_Miles_Reported: N/A - Only the spillway was removed and this is a dam on a very large lake.  The Downstream dam (Beaver Meadow Dam controls the water level of Beaver Lake)

Description: The Butternut Pond Dam, which was owned by the NH Fish and Game Department, was removed by NH Department of Enviornmental Services personnel in 2013.

A priority dam removal site identified in the McQuesten Brook Watershed Restoration Plan lead by the New Hampshire Rivers Council. This was an unregistered dam with no ownership linkage, and it resulted in the death of adult, wild, eastern brook trout during high flows. The dam was removed by the project partners to eliminate the mortality of trout and to improve AOP and geomorphic integrity in the watershed.

This project involved the removal of a dam built in 1831 on an important coastal river for migratory species. Dams have been at or near this site since the mid-1600s. The dam impoundment stretched for over four miles and blocked access to 21 miles of habitat. Migratory species were already returning during the construction, finding their way back to historic habitat after nearly four centuries.

A priority dam removal site identified in the McQuesten Brook Watershed Restoration Plan lead by the New Hampshire Rivers Council. This was an unregistered dam with no ownership linkage, and it created an impoundment called "McQuesten Pond". The pond is on the 303(d) list of impaired waters due to elevated levels of Chlorophyll-a and insufficient dissolved oxygen and oxygen saturation to support aquatic life (fish). Post-removal conditions will support designated uses and create more fish passage in the watershed, and alleviate flooding of adjacent businesses.
Original.Use: Base material for future residential road

Description: A priority dam removal site identified in the McQuesten Brook Watershed Restoration Plan lead by the New Hampshire Rivers Council. The pond is on the 303(d) list of impaired waters due to elevated levels of Chlorophyll-a and insufficient dissolved oxygen and oxygen saturation to support aquatic life (fish). Original.Use: Base material for future residential road

Description: The Lower Sawyer Mill Dam was the first dam on the Bellamy River and was located approximately 2,000 linear feet upstream of the head of tide (tributary to Great Bay). The dam removal was the first phase of a two phase project, which also includes removal of the Upper Sawyer Mill Dam. The Upper Dam is located approximately 350 feet  upstream of the Lower Dam and removal is planned for the summer of 2019. Removal of both dams will reconnect approximately 1 mile of mainstem river, provide passage and access to freshwater habitat for diadromous fish species and improve fish passage and help facilitate restoration efforts for an additional 5.9 miles of mainstem river.  Additionally, removal of the dams will restore approximately 21 acres of previously inundated wetlands, eliminate two unsafe dams, improve flood resiliency and restore water quality.
Miles_Restored_US: 1-mile after the Upper Dam is removed.
Miles_Restored_DS: The head of tide is located approximately 2,000 feet downstream of the dam.

Description: The Pool Colony Dam was removed by the National Park Service in 1999 as part of the agency's dam safety program, which states that NPS dams should either be maintained or drained.

This dam was originally built to provide water for a working mill owned by Henry Pursel.  By 1945, the mill was converted into a local Agway store.  More recently, the mill dam was in a state of disrepair, having been listed as a significant hazard by New Jersey dam safety officials.  Because the dam had outlived its original purpose and was a liability, the owner agreed to remove most of the structure.  The dam was the only blockage on Lopatcong Creek and its removal has opened up 10 miles of additional spawning habitat for American shad and other migratory species.  Benefits of the removal have already begun to be realized.  During the spring floods of 2006, adjacent property and the local Agway store escaped the flooding they have seen in years past.

This dam was built in the 19th century and reconstructed several times in the early 1900's to service a mill and also enable ice harvesting.  The dam experienced flood damage in 2000 and was severely deteriorated.  It also contributed to degraded water quality and blocked the movement of resident fishes such as brown trout.  The dam owners, who operate a restaurant near the dam, donated a parcel of river frontage to be available for public access once the dam, a public safety hazard, is removed. The total project is expected to cost approximately $200,000 with funding provided by federal, state, county, and private partners.  The Musconetcong Watershed Association, which is leading the project, considers the remaining 19 dams on the river to be candidates for dam removal as well.
Original.Use: Originally built to power a grist mill and allow for ice harvesting

Description: The Finesville Dam blocked some 3 miles of habitat for migratory fish on the Musconetcong River. It is expected that the project will restore access for migratory species including American eel, alewife, and blueback herring, with secondary benefits through increased food supply to striped bass within the main stem of the Delaware River.

Type_Material: Concrete & Rock Fill Encased within Two Rows of Steel Sheet Pile

Description: The removal of this dam restores natural flow and anadromous fish passage to 3 miles of the Raritan River for the first time since 1901. Its removal also improves recreational opportunities on the river. This is the third dam on the Raritan River to be removed since 2010.
Type_Material: Concrete Core with Stone Block Veneer

Description: In April 2013, Stone’s dam was removed from Hakihokake Creek in Milford after it was severely damaged during Hurricane Irene.
Type_Material: Concrete Core with Stone Block Veneer

Description: This dam was previously damaged in a storm event.
This dam was previously damaged in a storm event.
